Did my first full cow processing at my ranch.
First pic is my steer at 730am.
Second pic is the steer at 1130am.
That steer was raised on my ranch, died on my ranch, and the meat never left.
The butchers did exactly what I wanted, and gave suggestions about better cuts to get. I got to keep all the weird odd bits and learned a ton in the process.
Best part: only costs $1.25/lb to process, which is cheaper than most processors at THEIR place. Plus its faster, safer, less stress on the cow and much healthier meat for us.
Used Texas Mobile Butchers, amazing, highly recommend them if you're in Central Texas, if not, google "mobile butcher" in your area.

As many of you know, me and another family started a Waldorf-style school in Dripping Springs. One of the cool things about the school is the full time chef we have who makes lunch for all the kids and faculty every day.

We make as much of our food as possible ourselves, and source meat as locally as possible--which means things like lamb from my ranch.

This week I slaughtered two of my lambs, and the chef (@chefarangoldstein ) did a class for parents and students on how to butcher a lamb carcass down to primal cuts. It was so much fun, especially having the kids there sawing through bone or making sausage, and really understanding where their food comes from and how to make it.

Plus, the lamb was truly amazing. It came to my ranch at 3 months old, we slaughtered at 11 months, and I put nothing in it but grass and water. Best lamb I've ever had, so mild and tasty.

Next up for Max Ranch: a proper garden.

For all things garden, I listen to @kevinespiritu_

You know him as the charismatic founder in the @epicgardening videos.

But before he was a gardening star, Kevin was employee #3 at my old company. Lemme tell you at the real Kevin:

Kevin seems really nice in his videos doesn't he?

But that's not really who he is.

The truth: the dude is actually WAY nicer in real life.

He's not fake, but unlike almost all of YouTube and Insta "celebs" I know, he has a deep kindness that I dont see in his videos.

Obviously the video format has something to do with it, but he worked for me for years and I know him deeply--he's one of the nicest humans ever.

The highest compliment I can give someone is I'd let them babysit my kids.

Well, I think Kevin DID that a few times🤣

And does he REALLY know about gardening, or is he just googling shit?

Even though I love Kevin as a human, the god's honest truth is that he was a terrible employee.

He was our first marketing director, and for every brilliant thing he did, he would fuckup two things.

Why?

Lemme tell you a story:

Kevin came into a meeting in a great mood.

Tucker "Whats up Kev? You hit some amazing metrics?"

Kevin "Metrics? What?"

Tucker "Marketing metrics?"

Kevin "Oh. No. My marigolds are blooming great, I was just tending them."

WTF!!!

Literally, all he cared about--while he worked at a BOOK COMPANY--was his damn plants.

It became a running joke at my company that Kevin was running a gardening business on the side.

We eventually had to fire him because he just could never consistently deliver results.

It was a "friendly" firing to the extent thats possible, and we left as friends.

I had a feeling he was going to end up doing something cool. I even told him to focus on plants, since he loved them so much.

But I am impressed by what he's built with Epic Gardening.

Its so awesome to watch your friends figure it out and make the leap into doing something they love.

And when that thing blows up and gets huge, thats even more fun to watch.

Now I'm buying his gardening stuff and learning gardening from him.

A quick lesson on what I've learned about meat processing recently (for those who care):
We tested the two major different ways to process cows: using a conventional USDA processor, and using a mobile processor.
There was a CLEAR winner.
Benefit of a mobile processor: cow is processed quickly & never leaves your ranch, & isn't subject to USDA requirements, which are not ideal.
Big downside is that you don’t get to hang and dry age the meat, which is a big part of the flavor.
Price is about the same.
Dry aging is when the beef hangs in a walk-in for 3+ weeks, so the muscle breaks down & flavor develops.
Wet aging means steer is killed & butchered & put in plastic packages all in the same day.
You age the meat in the fridge for 3-4 weeks (or more) before you freeze it.
Some say the flavor is exactly the same.
So we got 2 steers—same breed, same genetics— processed at the same time.
One at our ranch with a mobile processor and wet aged.
One at a regular USDA processor, that was dry aged.
After even 1 taste test, it was glaringly obvious:
Dry aging is WAY better than wet aging.
It’s not even close. Wet aging SUCKS actually. The meat is so chewy and tough.
I think the big problem is that wet aging doesn’t allow the cow to go through rigor mortis. I can still taste and feel that toughness in the meat.
The other big issue was the cuts.
The mobile butchers cuts were sloppy—which is to be expected when cutting new muscle.
The conventional packers cut were precise—bc the meat had 3 weeks to hang and was much drier.

Sharing your truth is the hardest thing to do when writing a book. And while it’s not typically necessary when writing a prescriptive nonfiction (e.g. a business book), it IS essential when writing a memoir. Otherwise the book is pointless.

People wonder why books like ‘Can’t Hurt Me’ by @davidgoggins or ‘Wild’ by @cherylstrayed are so great and go onto sell millions of copies. It’s for one reason: They tell their whole truth. Their ugly, dark, sad truth that they’ve accepted about themselves. That’s what makes people love them.

What is the truth you are TERRIFIED to say but desperately want to heal from and integrate into your story? That deep dark truth about yourself that you rarely (or never) admit to others? The thing that — if you said it — would set you free?

That is the truth that can transform your life, and heal your soul.

If you want to tell your truth by writing it in a memoir, there’s no better person to guide you than @realtuckermax. He helped me with ‘Play It Away’ which totally changed my life for the better, and continues to sell every day and help people around the world. It’s not an easy path, but it’s tremendously fulfilling.

Tucker is running a private memoir group now. If that’s what you want to do, reach out to him.

(Special thanks to @thegrahamcochrane for the great interview and clip).
